            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Riley is a man etched by the Bay Area\u2019s persistent fog and fluctuating fortunes. Born and raised across the bay in Alameda, his upbringing was solidly working-class, centered on his father\u2019s work at the naval air station and his mother\u2019s role as a school secretary. Practicality was the family ethos, and David absorbed it. He enrolled in Business Administration at CSU East Bay, envisioning a stable, white-collar future, but that path was rerouted when his father suffered a debilitating back injury. To support his family, David dropped out and took a full-time stocking job at a grocery store chain\u2014a temporary measure that became a lifelong career.\n\nHis ascent was slow but steady, built on reliability rather than ambition. He moved from stocker to produce lead, then to assistant manager, finally landing the manager position at a bustling Marina district store a decade ago. The key turning point in his life wasn't professional, but personal. His marriage of fifteen years ended amicably but left him financially and emotionally drained. The divorce solidified his priorities: securing his own small condo in the Inner Richmond and ensuring his daughter, now a sophomore at UC Davis, would have the opportunities he didn't.\n\nDavid\u2019s life now runs on a predictable, comforting rhythm. His alarm sounds at 5:00 AM. By 6:15, he\u2019s on the 38 Geary bus for his 5.5-mile commute, listening to history podcasts and observing the city wake up. His work is a demanding cycle of inventory, scheduling, and customer service, managing a transient staff of students and lifers. Socially, his circle is small\u2014a weekly beer with a couple of old friends and Sunday phone calls with his daughter, who remains the undisputed center of his world.\n\nHe is a man deeply, quietly connected to his city. He grumbles about the exorbitant cost of living and the changing streetscape, yet finds profound peace in a foggy walk through Golden Gate Park. His dreams are modest but deeply felt: pay off his mortgage before he\u2019s 60, watch his daughter graduate debt-free, and maybe, just maybe, take a trip to Normandy to see the D-Day beaches he\u2019s only read about. David Riley represents the San Francisco that persists beneath the headlines\u2014a city of hardworking people carving out a meaningful life, one shift at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the sound his father made trying to get out of the armchair\u2014a sharp, pained gasp. In that instant, his business textbooks felt like fiction. The only reality was his dad\u2019s pain and his mom\u2019s worried glance. The choice wasn\u2019t a choice; it was a duty. Nineteen years old, he walked into the grocery store that afternoon and asked for an application. It was the moment he silently traded his own aspirations for his family\u2019s stability, cementing a lifetime of responsibility over ambition.\n\n2.\nThe day he dropped his daughter, Maya, at her UC Davis dorm was a blur of cardboard boxes and nervous energy. After the last hug, driving back to the city alone, he had to pull over near the Carquinez Bridge. It wasn\u2019t sadness, but an overwhelming wave of pride. Every sacrificed vacation, every pre-dawn shift stacking apples\u2014it was all for her, for this moment. Just two years ago, that feeling became the bedrock of his purpose, the absolute validation of his quiet, hardworking life.\n\n3.\nAfter the divorce, he spent his first night in the small Inner Richmond condo. He didn\u2019t unpack. He just sat on the floor, the smell of fresh paint in the air, and listened to the N Judah rumbling faintly a block away. This was his. Not rented, not temporary\u2014his. Earned with a thousand 5:00 AM alarms. That night, about nine years ago, he felt the solid ground of permanence for the first time in years, a profound, quiet victory against the city's relentless churn.\n\n4.\nHe stood in the empty apartment after his ex-wife had moved her last box. It wasn't angry, just hollow. He ran a hand over the indentations the sofa had left in the carpet after fifteen years. In that profound silence, a single, fierce priority crystallized: Maya. Everything from that point forward\u2014every schedule he wrote, every floor he mopped\u2014would be for her future. That day, over a decade ago, the ache of the end forged the unwavering focus that would define his next chapter.\n\n5.\nLast winter, during a particularly dense fog, he took his usual weekend walk around Stow Lake. The tops of the trees disappeared into a low, gray ceiling, muffling the city's noise to a distant hum. He sat on a damp bench, watching the ghost-like shapes of cormorants on the water. In this ancient-feeling stillness, the daily grind and his worries simply fell away. This was his city, the timeless, melancholic San Francisco he loved. That feeling of peace is a memory he consciously returns to and recreates."
